ggplot2

Unlike many other visualization packages, ggplot2 has its own grammar based on The Grammar of Graphics (reference 3). It is arguably the most prevalent visualization library in R.

A good R alternative is Plotly. We are going to focus on ggplot2 because it allows us to generate very complex graphs based on this structured grammar, generating complex graphs from relatively simple inputs.

In Python there is an implementation of ggplot2 called plotnine. Other classical python libraries for visualization are matplotlib, plotly or bokeh.

general structure of a ggplot graph:

The general way to express the grammar used in ggplot2 is shown below:

ggplot(data = <DATA>, mapping = aes(<MAPPINGS>) + 
  <GEOM_FUNCTION>(
     mapping = aes(<MAPPINGS>),
     stat = <STAT>, 
     position = <POSITION>
  ) +
  <FACET_FUNCTION> + 
  <COORDINATE_FUNCTION> +
  <THEME_FUNCTION>

At first this can be confusing, so it is best to illustrate how the grammar works thorugh examles. We will begin with scatterplots, histograms and barplots.

The diamonds dataset

With ggplot2 comes the very famous diamonds dataset. This dataset is widely used as an example in many tutorials you may find online. We are going to use it as well due to its clarity and relatively high number of variables. Be sure to run ?diamonds should you want to retrieve information about the dataset.

The dataset essentially contains information of roughly 54000 diamonds, focusing on their characteristics, price and quality. The figure below (taken from ref. 2) gives the definition of some of the variables:

Scatterplots

Let us apply the grammar detailed before to create some simple scatterplots. To specify the mappings we will use the special function aes() (aesthetics)

ggplot(diamonds, aes(x = carat, y = price)) +
  geom_point()

Let us break down the code above:

  • With ggplot() we are declaring that our data is contained in the dataframe diamonds and that we are going to use the variable carat for the x-axis and the variable price for the y axis.
  • Then we add a layer using geom_point(), which is used to create a scatterplot.

Coloring the scatter-plot

fixed color - color outside of aes()

To set an aesthetic such as the color to a fixed value, without scaling it, do so in the individual layer outside of aes()

ggplot(diamonds, aes(x = carat, y = price)) +
  geom_point(color = "red") +
  xlab("Carat variable") +
  ggtitle("Price of diamonds as a function of carat")

scaled color - color within of aes()

To color the scatter-plot following a third variable, we need to specify the color argument within an aesthetic (aes()). For example, we may specify the following so that each diamond cut type gets a different color:

ggplot(diamonds, aes(x = carat, y = price)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = cut)) +
  xlab("Carat variable") +
  ggtitle("Price of diamonds as a function of carat")

Adding trend lines

By specifying another geom, we may overlay different graph types. A typical case for scatterplots is to overlay a trend line using geom_smooth() and select the type of line with the argument method.

  • Example: fitting a linear model:
ggplot(diamonds, aes(x = carat, y = price)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm")
`geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

Fitting non-linear models is sometimes very useful because it can help spot non-linear relationships in your data.

  • Example: fitting a generalized additive model (useful non linear model when there are many points)
ggplot(diamonds, aes(x = carat, y = price)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "gam")
`geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ s(x, bs = "cs")'

Another typical example is to use method = "loess", which is a useful non-linear regression curve when there are not as many points as in the diamonds dataset. loess is much more computationally demanding, so you should consider an alternative (such as gam) when \(n > 1000\) (\(n =\) number of observations).

Other important aesthetics for scatterplots

For this examples I am going to resort the the mpg dataset (miles-per-gallon), which contains data about the fuel economy of different cars.

It contains less points than the diamonds dataset and therefore illustrates better some concepts. Again, you may run ?mpg to get specific information about the variables

We will use as x the variable cty (city miles per gallon) and as y the variable hwy (highway miles per gallon).

shape

The shape aesthetics may be used with categorical variables and it assigns a different shape to each category. It can deal with a maximum of 6 categories. In the example below, the SUV class is simply not plotted because there are more than 6 categories, so the last one is simply ommited.

mpg %>% 
  ggplot(aes(cty, hwy)) +
  geom_point(aes(shape = class))
Warning: The shape palette can deal with a maximum of 6 discrete values because
more than 6 becomes difficult to discriminate; you have 7. Consider
specifying shapes manually if you must have them.
Warning: Removed 62 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

size

The size aesthetic can be used with continuous or categorical variables, although with categoricals it does not make much sense, since categoricals do not necessarily have an implicit smaller than / greater than relationship (at least not directly). Let us use the number of engine cylinders as the size aesthetic:

mpg %>% 
  ggplot(aes(cty, hwy)) +
  geom_point(aes(size = cyl))

Scatterplot matrices

The diagonal can be a histogram or a kernel density estimation for instance.

This is not part of the core materials of the subject, but these graphs are typically used to try to determine potential relationships between several variables visually.

Adding a non-linear smoothing curve can be useful to identify potential non-linearities:

my_fn <- function(data, mapping, ...){
  p <- ggplot(data = data, mapping = mapping) + 
    geom_point() + 
    geom_smooth(method="gam", fill="blue", color="blue", ...)
  p
}

g = ggpairs(diamonds %>% select(carat, depth, table, price, x, y, z), 
            lower = list(continuous = my_fn))
g

Histogram

Histograms require a continuous numerical variable.

Creating a histogram is just as easy, the main difference being that we now need to use geom_histogram(). We also no longer need to specify a y aesthetic.

ggplot(diamonds, aes(x = price)) + 
  geom_histogram()
`stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

To color the histogram, we use the aesthetic fill. Using color would only affect the outline of each bar of the histogram

ggplot(diamonds, aes(x = price, fill = cut)) + 
  geom_histogram()
`stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

Note that the above graph might cause some confusion because each of the bars might be interpreted as being stacked on top of the preceding bar (which is not the case). Because of this we might want to separate the histograms for more clarity.

A first option is to filter the dataset. If we filter the dataset, we may create a histogram for only one of the cuts. First, lets remember how we can loop through the unique() values of the variable cut with a for loop (If you do not know how to use for loops in R, look for the syntax on reference 1 or refer to any online tutorial. The syntax below will suffice for our purposes though):

for (cut in (diamonds$cut %>% unique())) {
  print(cut)
}
[1] "Ideal"
[1] "Premium"
[1] "Good"
[1] "Very Good"
[1] "Fair"

Now lets use that for loop produce different filtered versions of our dataset and then create a histogram of each of those sub-datasets (one histogram per cut type). We are going to use the function list.append() from the package rlist (be sure to install it if it is not available) to store the graph produced during each iteration of the for loop:

# Initialize a list to store the output of the for loop
gr_list <- list()

for (cut_type in (diamonds$cut %>% unique())) {
  gr <- ggplot(data = diamonds %>% filter(cut == cut_type), aes(x = price, fill = cut)) + 
          geom_histogram() +
          ggtitle(cut_type)
  
  # Store the graph in the list
  # The function list.append requires the package rlist
  gr_list <- gr_list %>% list.append(gr)
}

# Print all the graphs stored in the list
gr_list

Faceting

We introduce here faceting in the context of histograms because it is an appropriate technique for the example at hand, but faceting is a general technique to display/explore the effect of sub-setting the data by the values of a third categorical variable. Essentially faceting does the following:

  1. Subsets the data following the unique values of the specified categorical variable(s) (if more than one variable is specified, for all unique combinations of those variables).
  2. Creates tables of graphs corresponding to those sub-datasets.

There are two faceting functions within ggplot2:

  • facet_wrap(): use it when you want to split your data by one or more categorical variables and do not need a matrix-like ordered output (if you need a matrix-like order output, use facet_grid()).
  • facet_grid(): use it when you want to split your data by 2 categorical variables. It has the additional advantage of providing a clear matrix-like ordered output.

facet_wrap() and facet_grid() are important and are better understood through examples, so lets see a bunch of them.

facet_wrap() - examples

We specify a string within facet_wrap with the categorical variable by which we would like to subset the data:

ggplot(diamonds, aes(x=price)) + 
  geom_histogram() + 
  facet_wrap("cut")
`stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

Each of the 5 histograms above corresponds to diamonds with a specific cut (either Fair, Good, Very Good, Premium or Ideal). This avoids the problems of the interpretation about stacking that might arise when generating a single histogram colored by cut, as we mentioned before.

Faceting can be applied to other geoms!

This is an example in-between included just to show you that faceting can be applied to other geoms, not only to geom_histogram()

Let us check an example from the mpg dataset. Lets produce a scatter-plot of the variables displ (cylinder displacement) and hwy (highway mileage).

ggplot(mpg, aes(displ, hwy)) + 
  geom_point()

Again, this output contains the entirety of the dataset. We may however want to create a different scatterplot for cars with the same engine drive (variable drv), where

  • f = front-wheel drive
  • r = rear wheel drie
  • 4wd = four wheel drive
ggplot(mpg, aes(displ, hwy)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  facet_wrap("drv")

The scatterplots above are comparable (all of them have the same ranges of x and y) and they allow us to analyze how the sub-sets of cars with different engine drive compare.

Facetting by more than one variable:

If you need to, you may split your data by more than one categorical variables. In this case you need to specify a vector of characters (strings) containing the names of the variables used for sub-setting. You can attain this in R using the function c() (combine).

The problem with this is two-fold:

  1. Your sub-sets of data might get too small if you specify many categorical variables for sub-setting. You need to ponder if that level of sub-setting is appropriate for your dataset.
  2. The combination of unique values for both categorical variables may result in a lot of sub-graphs. You may need to re-scale the output.

Let us for example create the same scatterplot with the mpg dataset, but this time let us facet_wrap by both engine drive (drv) and number of cylinders (cyl):

ggplot(mpg, aes(displ, hwy)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  facet_wrap(c("drv", "cyl"))

The title of each scatterplot gives us the specific combination of the variables drv and cyl to which the scatterlpot corresponds. See for example how there are very few cars with front wheel drive and 5 cylinders (f 5), resulting in a scatterplot that is barely populated. The same occurs for cars with front-wheel drive and 8 cylinders (f 8). This is one of the risks of faceting by too many variables, some of your subsets of data may become too small.

nrow and ncol in facet_wrap()

You can use the arguments nrow and ncol to control the number of rows and columns created by facet_wrap(). You may only specify one of these arguments, the other will be automatically calculated to match the number of unique combinations of the variables:

ggplot(mpg, aes(displ, hwy)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  facet_wrap(c("drv","cyl"), nrow = 2)

facet_grid()

Most useful when you want to facet your plot on the combination of two categorical variables and there is data available for all combinations. The formula should contain two variable names separated by a ~. For your information, the character ~ is called tilde.

  • The variable specified on the left of the tilde (~) will be faceted row-wise
  • The variable specified on the right of the tilde (~) will be faceted column-wise
# The variable drv gets faceted row-wise
# The variable number of cylinders gets faceted coumn-wise
ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  facet_grid(drv ~ cyl)

Again we see for example that there are now cars with four wheel drive and 5 cylinders (row = 4, column = 5). The same occurs for cars with rear-wheel and 5 cylinders (row = r and column = 5) or for cars with rear wheel and 4 cylinders (row = r and column = 4).

facet_grid() with only one categorical variable

If you do not want to facet in either rows or columns and wish to specify only one categorical, use . in the corresponding dimension. For example:

  • facet_grid(. ~ cyl) would facet the variable number of cylinders cyl column-wise and not include any other variable.
ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  facet_grid(. ~ cyl) # facet only column-wise, not row-wise

  • facet_grid(drv ~ .) would facet the variable type of drive drv row-wise and not include any other variable.
ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  facet_grid(drv ~ .) # facet only row-wise, not column-wise

after_stat() - histogram of relative frequencies

A histogram is by default built with the absolute frequencies, that is, with the total number of observations within each of the bins of the histogram.

If we want to produce a histogram of relative frequencies (the relative frequency is the absolute frequency divided by the total number of observations), the syntax is a little bit tricky, but this is the fastest way to do it in ggplot. We will focus only on previous diamonds.

ggplot(data = diamonds %>% filter(cut == "Premium"), aes(x = price, fill = cut)) + 
    geom_histogram(aes(y = after_stat(count / sum(count)))) +
    labs(y = "relative frequency")
`stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

Barplots

Basic barplot

A barplot contains:

  • a categorical/discrete variable in the x-axis
  • absolute frequencies in the y-axis.

Let us use a group_by() to check the number of diamonds in each color category:

diamonds %>% 
  group_by(color) %>% 
  summarize(
    n = n()
  )
# A tibble: 7 Ã 2
  color     n
  <ord> <int>
1 D      6775
2 E      9797
3 F      9542
4 G     11292
5 H      8304
6 I      5422
7 J      2808

We may obtain a graphical representation of this using a bar plot with the following code (output printed further down below):

ggplot(diamonds, aes(x = color)) +
  geom_bar()

By default geom_bar() uses the argument stat = "count". This is the default, unless we override it (see later section on stat = "identity") and it does the following:

  1. Counts the number of rows corresponding to each value of the categorical variable x, in this case color.
  2. Prints a bar indicating that row count for each category (for each value of x). That is why we do not need to specify any variable y, the count is the varible y.

Further down below we clarify how to override this behavior using stat = "identity". Let us now run the code above to see the output:

ggplot(diamonds, aes(x = color)) +
  geom_bar()

after_stat() + barplot of relative frequencies

The above barplot shows the absolute frequencies of each category. If we want reltaive frequencies (absolute frequencies divided by the total number of observations), the syntax is similar to that used for creating a histogram of relative frequencies

ggplot(diamonds, aes(x = color)) +
  geom_bar(aes(y = after_stat(count / sum(count)))) +
  labs(y = "relative frequency")

coordinate_flip()

Sometimes you might want to flip the bars. You can do this as follows:

ggplot(diamonds, aes(x = color)) +
  geom_bar() +
  coord_flip()

Position argument

3 options:

  • position = "stack"
  • position = "dodge"
  • position = "fill"

The default is âstackâ. This places bars corresponding to different values of the specified categorical on top of each other (each bar starts where the last bar ends).

ggplot(diamonds, aes(x = color)) + 
  geom_bar(aes(fill = cut), position = "stack")

Stacking can cause confusion or can be misinterpreted. Your audience could interpret that the bars overlay (all bars start at 0) or that the graphs are stacked on top of each other (each bar starts counting where the last one ends, which is actually the case in ggplot).

To avoid this possibility for multiple interpretations caused the stacking, you may also use âdodgeâ

ggplot(diamonds, aes(x = color)) + 
  geom_bar(aes(fill = cut), position = "dodge")

Finally, if you want to highlight the percent distribution within each category you may use position = fill. However this may lead your audience to think for example that there are as many âgoodâ diamonds in color E than in color J, when in reality there are many more good diamonds with the color E (see the previous dodged graph):

ggplot(diamonds, aes(x = color)) + 
  geom_bar(aes(fill = cut), position = "fill")

stat = "identity" - barplots of variables other than count

By default geom_bar() counts the number of rows to produce the output of the y variable count.

We may however pre-process the data to create the desired numerical value per category and then use stat = "identity" to indicate that we want to set that value as the y aesthetic instead of the default row-counting.

As an example, let us compute the average price of diamonds for each combination of cut and clarity using group_by and summarize:

aux <-
  diamonds %>% 
    group_by(cut, clarity) %>% 
    summarize(
      n_diamonds = n(), # counts the number of diamonds in each group
      avg_price = mean(price)
    )
`summarise()` has grouped output by 'cut'. You can override using the `.groups`
argument.
aux

If we attempt to create a barplot as before we get some weird output. Can you give an interpretation of this? (solution will be given after class in this same notebook)

ggplot(aux, aes(x = cut, fill = clarity)) +
  geom_bar()

By default geom_bar() uses stat = "count", which creates the count varaible based
on the number of rows corresponding to each category.

We get the output above because in the dataframe aux there are 8 rows 
corresponding to every `cut`

With regard to the colors, since each category `cut` can be further split 
into 8 clarity categories we get a value of 1 for every color, since there is
only one row per combination of `cut` and `clarity`

To produce the desired output we need to specify avg_price as the y aesthetic. When explicitly specifying a y variable in a bar plot you also need to specify stat = "identity" to override the default stat = "count" (which counts the number of rows). Otherwise you will get an error (feel free to check this):

ggplot(aux, aes(x = cut, y = avg_price, fill = clarity)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity")

Understanding the default stat = "count"

Now that you know how to use stat = "identity", we may explore how the default stat = "count" works. Let us remember the behavior of the basic bar plot. Essentially the code below counts the number of diamonds within each color category assigns that to the y variable.

ggplot(diamonds, aes(x = color)) +
  geom_bar()

We attain the same if we explicitly state the default argument stat = "count"

# This is exactly the same, only making the default 
# argument stat = "count" explicit
ggplot(diamonds, aes(x = color)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "count")

Now let us create an aux intermediate result using group_by() to count the number of diamonds in each group and then use stat = "identity" to depict that as the y variable. You will see we reach the exact same output:

aux <- 
  diamonds %>% 
    group_by(color) %>% 
    summarize(
      n_diamonds = n() # count the number of diamonds in each color category
    )

ggplot(aux, aes(x = color, y = n_diamonds)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity")

At this point the difference between stat = "count" and stat = "identity" should be clear to you.
